//✅ 1. Basic Traversal & Observations
//* Leaders in an array


//PROBLEM STATEMENT--------

/*

Problem
You are given an integer array nums.
An element in the array is called a leader if it is strictly greater than every element to its right.
The last element of the array is always a leader.
Return all leader elements in the same order they appear in the array.

Function Declaration
Function Name: findLeaders
This function finds all the leader elements in the given array.

Parameter
nums → an integer array of size n
Return Value
A list containing all leader elements in the order they appear in the original array.

Constraints
1 ≤ nums.length ≤ 10⁵
-10⁴ ≤ nums[i] ≤ 10⁴

Input Format
The first line contains an integer T — number of test cases.
For each test case:
The first line contains an integer n — size of the array.
The second line contains n space-separated integers representing the array.

Output Format
For each test case, print all leader elements in the array in the same order, separated by spaces.

Sample Input
1
6
10 7 8 3 5 2

Sample Output
10 8 5 2

Explanation
Array: 10 7 8 3 5 2
2 → last element → leader
5 > 2 → leader
8 > 3, 5, 2 → leader
10 > all elements to its right → leader
Leaders: 10 8 5 2

Sample Input
1
5
6 -2 9 4 1

Sample Output
9 4 1

Explanation
Array: 6 -2 9 4 1
1 → last element → leader
4 > 1 → leader
9 > 4, 1 → leader
Leaders: 9 4 1

*/


//SOLUTION-----

/*
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findLeaders(int[] nums) {
         
            List<Integer> leaders = new ArrayList<>();
        
        int n = nums.length;
        
       
        int rightMax = nums[n - 1];
        leaders.add(rightMax);
        
        
        for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (nums[i] > rightMax) {
                rightMax = nums[i];
                leaders.add(rightMax);
            }
        }
        
     
        Collections.reverse(leaders);
        
        return leaders;
        
    }
}
*/

